SIMPLE: haunt
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Haunt
<hw>Haunt</hw> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧nt; 277)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Haunted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Haunting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>hanter</ets>; of uncertain origin, perh. from an assumed LL.
<ets>ambitare</ets> to go about, fr. L. <ets>ambire</ets> (see
<er>Ambition</er>); or cf. Icel. <ets>heimta</ets> to demand, regain,
akin to <ets>heim</ets> home (see <er>Home</er>). ⟦root⟧36.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To frequent; to resort to frequently; to visit
pertinaciously or intrusively; to intrude upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You wrong me, sir, thus still to <qex>haunt</qex> my house.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those cares that <qex>haunt</qex> the court and town.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inhabit or frequent as a specter; to visit as a
ghost or apparition; -- said of spirits or ghosts, especially of dead
people; <as>as, the murdered man <ex>haunts</ex> the house where he
died</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Foul spirits <qex>haunt</qex> my resting place.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To practice; to devote one's self to.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That other merchandise that men <qex>haunt</qex> with fraud . . .
is cursed.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leave honest pleasure, and <qex>haunt</qex> no good pastime.</q>
<rj><qau>Ascham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To accustom; to habituate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Haunt</qex> thyself to pity.</q>
<rj><qau>Wyclif.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haunt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Haunt
<hw>Haunt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To persist in staying or
visiting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I've charged thee not to <qex>haunt</qex> about my doors.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haunt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Haunt
<hw>Haunt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place to which one
frequently resorts; <as>as, drinking saloons are the <ex>haunts</ex> of
tipplers; a den is the <ex>haunt</ex> of wild beasts.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In Old English the place occupied by any one as a
dwelling or in his business was called a <xex>haunt</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note>
<p>Often used figuratively.</p>

<p><q>The household nook,⟦br⟧
The <qex>haunt</qex> of all affections pure.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj></p>

<p><q>The feeble soul, a <qex>haunt</qex> of fears.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>
</note>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The habit of resorting to a place.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>haunt</qex> you have got about the courts.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Practice; skill.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of clothmaking she hadde such an <qex>haunt</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haunted</ent>⟦br⟧
